]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>job perspective</subject><webLink xml:lang="nl"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><programDescription xml:lang="nl"><![CDATA[The Master's programme in Conflict Resolution and Governance offers the opportunity to develop a command of the resources needed to respond to the analytic challenges presented by conflicts and to situate contemporary events in a historical and comparative perspective. 

The goal is to train students to draw on the most vexing conflicts to fashion governance regimes from the fabric of local crisis. 

Amsterdam is known as a model of political, religious and intellectual tolerance. The International Court of Justice in The Hague has made the Netherlands one of the world's most important centres for international conflict resolution. Many of the lecturers are researchers in institutes affiliated with the University, including the Amsterdam School for Social science Research (ASSR), the Institute for Migration and Ethnic Studies (IMES) and the Amsterdam Research Institute for Global Issues and Development Studies (AGIDS). Their broad range of interests provides students with a complex and thorough picture of the factors influencing the development and resolution of conflicts in today's world.]]></programDescription><programDescription xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[The Master's programme in Conflict Resolution and Governance offers the opportunity to develop a command of the resources needed to respond to the analytic challenges presented by conflicts and to situate contemporary events in a historical and comparative perspective. 

